{"title_page": "Valley of Stars", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area  \n| name = Valley of Stars \n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Chah Kooh Valley (Qeshm) 003.jpg\n| photo_caption = Sand dunes in the Valley of Stars \n| map_image = Persian gulf qeshm.jpg\n| map_caption = \n| label = Valley of Stars\n| label_position = right\n| location = [[Qeshm Island]]\n| nearest_city = [[Qeshm]], [[Hormozgan]], [[Iran]]\n| coords      = {{coord|26|41|43|N|55|37|06|E|scale:500000_source:GNS|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|3,373,063|acre|sqmi ha km2}}\n| established = \n| visitation_num = est 1,000,000\n| visitation_year = 2014\n| visitation_ref = \n| governing_body = [[Iran]]'s [[National Park]] Service\n}}\n\n'''Valley of Stars''', also known as '''Stars Valley''', is a valley located on [[Qeshm]], an [[Iran]]ian island in the [[Strait of Hormuz]] in [[Hormozgan Province]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Earth Science Picture of the Day: Stars Valley on Qeshm Island, Iran|url=http://epod.usra.edu/blog/2012/05/stars-valley-on-qeshm-island-iran.html|publisher=Universities Space Research Association|accessdate=5 March 2016|date=May 12, 2012}}</ref> It is located north of the village of [[Berkeh-ye Khalaf]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Valley of Stars on Qeshm Island (PHOTOS)|url=http://iranfrontpage.com/iran-photos/2015/05/valley-of-stars-on-qeshm-island-photos/|publisher=Iran Front Page.|accessdate=5 March 2016|date=May 26, 2015}}</ref> it is a local story that said: a star fell down from the sky and hit the ground right in the heart and shaped a giant, mysterious, and weird valley which we call it Stars Valley or Valley of Stars now. This geographical site is one of the most unique natural attractions in Qeshm and Iran.\n\n== About stars valley ==\n<br />\n\n== About Stars Valley ==\nStars Valley or Valley of Stars is located in Qeshm Island and it is definitely on your \u201cMUST SEE\u201d list in Qeshm. As mentioned, based on local anecdotes, a star hit the ground and shaped this valley. Well, locals aren\u2019t entirely wrong. Scientific investigations on this place revealed that this phenomenon might be formed by a cosmic in the first place. Moreover, the mysterious shapes inside this valley are made by water and wind erosions. This attraction is unique because you can only find these kinds of geographical sites in Iran and Arizona, USA. Although we now know no stars involve in shaping Stars Valley, in the night sky, you can see hundreds of stars with naked eyes and that alone, justifies the name \u201cValley of Stars\u201d.[https://apochi.com/attractions/qeshm/stars-valley/]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Hormozgan Province]]\n[[Category:Qeshm County]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Asia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Hormozgan Province]]\n\n{{Iran-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area  \n| name = Valley of Stars \n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Chah Kooh Valley (Qeshm) 003.jpg\n| photo_caption = Sand dunes in the Valley of Stars \n| map_image = Persian gulf qeshm.jpg\n| map_caption = \n| label = Valley of Stars\n| label_position = right\n| location = [[Qeshm Island]]\n| nearest_city = [[Qeshm]], [[Hormozgan]], [[Iran]]\n| coords      = {{coord|26|41|43|N|55|37|06|E|scale:500000_source:GNS|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|3,373,063|acre|sqmi ha km2}}\n| established = \n| visitation_num = est 1,000,000\n| visitation_year = 2014\n| visitation_ref = \n| governing_body = [[Iran]]'s [[National Park]] Service\n}}\n\n'''Valley of Stars''', also known as '''Stars Valley''', is a valley located on [[Qeshm]], an [[Iran]]ian island in the [[Strait of Hormuz]] in [[Hormozgan Province]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Earth Science Picture of the Day: Stars Valley on Qeshm Island, Iran|url=http://epod.usra.edu/blog/2012/05/stars-valley-on-qeshm-island-iran.html|publisher=Universities Space Research Association|accessdate=5 March 2016|date=May 12, 2012}}</ref> It is located north of the village of [[Berkeh-ye Khalaf]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Valley of Stars on Qeshm Island (PHOTOS)|url=http://iranfrontpage.com/iran-photos/2015/05/valley-of-stars-on-qeshm-island-photos/|publisher=Iran Front Page.|accessdate=5 March 2016|date=May 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Hormozgan Province]]\n[[Category:Qeshm County]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Asia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Hormozgan Province]]\n\n{{Iran-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mhmdsbr", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valley_of_Stars"}
{"title_page": "Sarvaiya", "text_new": "{{use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{rewrite|date=February 2020}}\nThe '''Sarvaiya''' also spelled ''Sarvaiyya'', ''Sarvia'', ''Sarwia'' are a [[Rajput]] clan of India, mainly found in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=State)|first=Bombay (India :|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&hl=en&ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAw#v=snippet&q=SARVAIYA%20CHUDASAMA&f=false|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency ...|date=1884|publisher=Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to the [[Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency]],The Sarvaiyas come from a branch of the [[Chudasama]]s, who are themselves a branch of the [[Samma (tribe)|Samma Rajput]]s. They ruled over [[Amreli]], Hathasnsi, [[Jesar]], [[Datha State|Datha]], [[Vasavad]], Santhli, Chital, [[Savarkundla|Kundla]], [[Bhavnagar|Gohilwad]], Chhatrasa, Chiroda, Chok, Pan, Ranigam, and other estates in [[Kathiawar]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cotton|first=James Sutherland|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=CIoZAAAAYAAJ|title=Imperial Gazetteer of India ...|last2=Burn|first2=Sir Richard|last3=Meyer|first3=Sir William Stevenson|date=1908|publisher=Clarendon Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gujarat (India)|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ|title=Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli|date=1972|publisher=Directorate of Government Print., Stationery and Publications, Gujarat State|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSarvaiya kingdom like the Chudasamas, were attacked in 1476 by Sultan [[Mahmud Begada]] . When Mahmud Begada, attacked Amreli, after taking over Junagadh from Chudasama, the Sarvaiya rulers of Amreli notably the two brothers Jesaji and Vejaji  for fighting against troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda, became outlaws, in order to re conquer Amreli.  Jesaji and Vejaji were able to get jagir of 64 villages from sultanate of Mohmud Begda  after fighting by remaining in outlawry for twelve years. Subsequently they settled in Hathasni. Later, the brothers divided the new estate between them, Jesoji receiving Hathasni and Vejoji estate of Jesar.<ref name=b>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&ct=result&id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&q=SARVAIYA+#search_anchor] Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA] Gazetteer, 1884</ref>\n\nThe fort of ''Vejalkotha'' also known as ''Vejalkot'' is named after its founder Sarvaiya Vejoji who fought with troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda from there, which is located in [[Girnar]] on eastern bank of Raval river and is now an archaeological site of interest.<ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=K-fRTYO7OIrYrQeZ6r2_CQ&ct=result&id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&dq=SARVAIYA&q=vejalkotha#search_anchor]</ref><ref name=g>[http://www.archive.org/stream/archaeologicals00indigoog/archaeologicals00indigoog_djvu.txt List of Arohitiotural Structures and othir Remains in the Province of Kathuwad. 19. Vejalkot, N. of TJnft, and Khibra Darw&ja, of brick.] Archaeological Survey of Western India, 1865.</ref>\n\nSome archaeological evidence and inscriptions mentioning this facts have been found and unearthed like Hathsani inscription and others found among ruins of Vejalkot.<ref name=g/><ref name=t/>\n\nThey were thus reduced to small estate and village chiefs after they left Amreli and their old glory. However, till the time of independence, the princely state of Jesar, Hathsani, Datha and nearby estates were ruled by Sarvaiya Rajputs. The [[Jesar State]]  and [[Datha princely state]] along with other Princely States was merged into Union of India to form the [[United State of Kathiawar]].<ref name=t>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=PHBDAAAAYAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=VOTRTZnkNMTxrQf2l9y0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC4Q6AEwATge HATHSANI INSCRIPTION : HATHSANI is a separate tribute paying State held by some Sarvaiya Rajputs in Und-Sarvaiyawad, sub-division of the [[Gohelwad]] [[Prant]] in Kathiawar] Indian antiquary, Volume 15</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=c70MAAAAIAAJ&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAQ Jesar is situated in the Und sub-division of the Gohilvad district. It is about eight miles south-west of Chok thanah, sixteen miles southwest of Palitana, and twenty-four miles east of Kundla. The Grasias are Sarvaiyas Rajputs and trace their origin from Amreli Sarvaiyas, who it seems were Bhayad of Sarva]</ref>\n\n==Surname==\nSarvaiya, Sawaria surname is however found also among other castes of Gujarat like [[Prajapati]], [[Mestri (community)|Mestri]], [[Kadiya Kshatriya]].{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ra Navghan]], the ruler of [[Junagadh]] is a common ancestor of Sarvaiya, [[Raijada]] and Chudasama Rajput clans.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Rajput Groups|state=collapsed}}\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Lunar dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "{{use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{rewrite|date=February 2020}}\nThe '''Sarvaiya''' also spelled ''Sarvaiyya'', ''Sarvia'', ''Sarwia'' are a [[Rajput]] clan of India, mainly found in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to the [[Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency]],The Sarvaiyas come from a branch of the [[Chudasama]]s, who are themselves a branch of the [[Samma (tribe)|Samma Rajput]]s. They ruled over Datha.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=State)|first=Bombay (India :|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&hl=en&ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAw#v=snippet&q=SARVAIYA%20CHUDASAMA&f=false|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency ...|date=1884|publisher=Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref> Among other estates that they ruled were [[Amreli]], Hathasnsi, [[Jesar]], [[Datha State|Datha]], [[Vasavad]],<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gujarat (India)|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ|title=Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli|date=1972|publisher=Directorate of Government Print., Stationery and Publications, Gujarat State|language=en}}</ref> Santhli, Chital, [[Savarkundla|Kundla]], [[Bhavnagar|Gohilwad]], Chhatrasa, Chiroda, Chok, Pan, Ranigam, and other estates in [[Kathiawar]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cotton|first=James Sutherland|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=CIoZAAAAYAAJ|title=Imperial Gazetteer of India ...|last2=Burn|first2=Sir Richard|last3=Meyer|first3=Sir William Stevenson|date=1908|publisher=Clarendon Press|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSarvaiya kingdom like the Chudasamas, were attacked in 1476 by Sultan [[Mahmud Begada]] . When Mahmud Begada, attacked Amreli, after taking over Junagadh from Chudasama, the Sarvaiya rulers of Amreli notably the two brothers Jesaji and Vejaji  for fighting against troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda, became outlaws, in order to re conquer Amreli.  Jesaji and Vejaji were able to get jagir of 64 villages from sultanate of Mohmud Begda  after fighting by remaining in outlawry for twelve years. Subsequently they settled in Hathasni. Later, the brothers divided the new estate between them, Jesoji receiving Hathasni and Vejoji estate of Jesar.<ref name=b>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&ct=result&id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&q=SARVAIYA+#search_anchor] Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA] Gazetteer, 1884</ref>\n\nThe fort of ''Vejalkotha'' also known as ''Vejalkot'' is named after its founder Sarvaiya Vejoji who fought with troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda from there, which is located in [[Girnar]] on eastern bank of Raval river and is now an archaeological site of interest.<ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=K-fRTYO7OIrYrQeZ6r2_CQ&ct=result&id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&dq=SARVAIYA&q=vejalkotha#search_anchor]</ref><ref name=g>[http://www.archive.org/stream/archaeologicals00indigoog/archaeologicals00indigoog_djvu.txt List of Arohitiotural Structures and othir Remains in the Province of Kathuwad. 19. Vejalkot, N. of TJnft, and Khibra Darw&ja, of brick.] Archaeological Survey of Western India, 1865.</ref>\n\nSome archaeological evidence and inscriptions mentioning this facts have been found and unearthed like Hathsani inscription and others found among ruins of Vejalkot.<ref name=g/><ref name=t/>\n\nThey were thus reduced to small estate and village chiefs after they left Amreli and their old glory. However, till the time of independence, the princely state of Jesar, Hathsani, Datha and nearby estates were ruled by Sarvaiya Rajputs. The [[Jesar State]]  and [[Datha princely state]] along with other Princely States was merged into Union of India to form the [[United State of Kathiawar]].<ref name=t>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=PHBDAAAAYAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=VOTRTZnkNMTxrQf2l9y0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC4Q6AEwATge HATHSANI INSCRIPTION : HATHSANI is a separate tribute paying State held by some Sarvaiya Rajputs in Und-Sarvaiyawad, sub-division of the [[Gohelwad]] [[Prant]] in Kathiawar] Indian antiquary, Volume 15</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=c70MAAAAIAAJ&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAQ Jesar is situated in the Und sub-division of the Gohilvad district. It is about eight miles south-west of Chok thanah, sixteen miles southwest of Palitana, and twenty-four miles east of Kundla. The Grasias are Sarvaiyas Rajputs and trace their origin from Amreli Sarvaiyas, who it seems were Bhayad of Sarva]</ref>\n\n==Surname==\nSarvaiya, Sawaria surname is however found also among other castes of Gujarat like [[Prajapati]], [[Mestri (community)|Mestri]], [[Kadiya Kshatriya]].{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ra Navghan]], the ruler of [[Junagadh]] is a common ancestor of Sarvaiya, [[Raijada]] and Chudasama Rajput clans.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Rajput Groups|state=collapsed}}\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Lunar dynasty]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Improvement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarvaiya"}
{"title_page": "Tom Haddon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Tom Haddon\n|fullname       = Thomas Haddon\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|LK}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = New Zealand\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|club1          = [[City Rovers]]\n|year1start     = 1918\n|year1end       = 19\n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 3\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 9\n|club2               = [[North Shore Albions]]\n|year2start          = 1925\n|year2end            = \n|appearances2        = 9 \n|tries2              = 4\n|goals2              = 0\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 12\n|teamA          = Auckland\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          =1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 2\n|triesB              = 0\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             = 0\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\nTom Haddon was a New Zealand rugby league player. He was Kiwi number 136 after playing two tests for New Zealand against Australia in 1919.\n\n==Early Life==\nIt is unclear where Thomas Haddon was born or raised. The first clear indication of him being in Auckland is with his debut for [[City Rovers]] in the opening game of the [[1918 Auckland Rugby League season]]. There are no records of him being born or marrying in [[New Zealand]]. At the start of 1920 he was thought to have moved to [[Australia]] to play rugby league but there are no records of him playing there after being given permission by the New Zealand Rugby League Council.\n\n==Playing career==\n===City Rovers, Auckland, and New Zealand===\nTom Haddon first appeared for [[City Rovers]] in 1918 in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition, playing for them against [[Grafton Athletic]] in a preliminary round to open the season <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Northern Union/Teams for Saturday/North Shore\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume XLIX, Issue 99\n| date = 1918-04-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19180426.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He scored a try in a Round 3 match against Grafton Athletic at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] where he \u201creceived a cross-kick and scored underneath the posts\u201d with City going on to win 11-10 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championship Matches/Newton V Ponsonby/Grafton V City\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16860\n| date = 1918-05-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180527.2.62.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. He scored against the same opponents in the second round in front of 5,000 spectators again at Victoria Park <ref>{{cite news\n| title =City Defeats Grafton\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16896\n| date = 1918-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180708.2.50\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nHe was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team in 1918 and played in the first proper inter provincial match that Auckland had played since [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|1915]] (when they played Thames twice, and Lower Waikato once). During the war the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had decided to largely cease its representative program. Haddon\u2019s debut was against [[Canterbury rugby league team]] and it resulted in a comfortable 45-9 victory to Auckland with Haddon scoring twice. The match was played in front of 10,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Haddon was again playing for City and in a round two match against [[North Shore Albions]] on the Devonport Domain in front of 500 spectators <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championships Continue/City V North Shore\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17158\n| date = 1919-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190512.2.21.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>. On August 9, Haddon played for Auckland in a match against [[Hawke's Bay rugby league team|Hawke's Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] before a crowd of 9,000. Haddon scored 3 tries in a 38 to 13 victory <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. As this was to be his last game for Auckland it meant that he had scored 3 tries for his City team in 2 full seasons of club rugby league but managed to cross the line 5 times for Auckland in just 2 appearances.\n\nHaddon had been picked to tour Australia with the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team in June and July of 1919 but due to circumstances was unable to make the trip <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football/Northern Union\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 65\n| date = 1920-03-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200316.2.67.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He was however selected for the 3rd and 4th tests against the touring Australian team in August/September <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. On September 6, Tom Haddon became Kiwi number 136 when he played lock in front of 24,300 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]]. New Zealand were defeated 34 to 23 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Inter-Colonial League/The Kiwi and the Kangaroo\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 213\n| date = 1909-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190908.2.129\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. In the third test also played on the Domain, New Zealand was heavily beaten by 32 points to 2 with Haddon moving into the prop position <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The Last Test/Australia\u2019s Decisive Win\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume 219, Issue L\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190915.2.98\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nIn April, 1920 [[Auckland Rugby League]] gave its permission for Haddon to \u201cplay in any district outside Auckland\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The Auckland League\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17447\n| date = 1920-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200417.2.80.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then on May 10 the [[New Zealand Rugby League|New Zealand Rugby League Council]] granted him an open transfer to play in Australia as reported in the ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The New Zealand Council\n| page = 6\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17467\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200511.2.96.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The ''[[Auckland Star]]'' suggesting that he \u201cwill probably play in Australia\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Affairs in Wellington/N.Z. Council Meets\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 112\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200511.2.96\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. It is however unclear as to where he went and if he played rugby league over the following years.\n\n===North Shore Albions===\nIn 1925 Haddon resumed playing rugby league in Auckland, this time however he was to represent the [[North Shore Albions]] who at this time were in fact named [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] after amalgamating with the Sunnyside League Football Club at the start of the 1920 season <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Two Clubs Amalgamate\n| page =6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVII| issue=17436\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200405.2.100\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. The first mention of him in a Devonport uniform is in a match against his old City team at [[Carlaw Park]] where he scored a try <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Another Great Game/City Beat Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 133,\n| date = 1925-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250608.2.147\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The day was significant for other reasons as the teams stood in silence before the kick off out of respect for [[Bill Stormont]] (Kiwi #140) who had died two days earlier. In a July match Haddon scored a try in front of 9,000 spectators at Carlaw Park against [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. Devonport won but not before Haddon was sent off along with Marist\u2019s New Zealand international [[Andrew O\u2019Brien (rugby league)|Jim O\u2019Brien]] after a \u201crough-up\u201d between the two. Devonport won the match 19-11 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Devonport\u2019s Day Out/Marists v Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 145\n| date = 1925-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250622.2.108\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nAfter a July match between Ponsonby and Devonport it was said of Haddon \u201cit is surprising how youth sticks to some footballers. On Saturday the veteran \u2026 was easily Devonport\u2019s best forward. He showed a lot of pace and some of the form displayed several years ago when playing for [[City Rovers|City]]\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football Notes and Comments/The North Shore Players\n| page =6 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19069\n| date = 1925-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250714.2.9.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then against Athletic \u201cHaddon, following up fast secured, and beating several Athletic players, scored behind the posts with three men hanging on to him\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Club Competitions/Athletic v Devonport\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 169\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250720.2.137\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. He scored a second try later in the match after a \u201cpassing rush\u201d in which all the Devonport players took part. Haddon\u2019s final ever senior league match was in a Roope Rooster semi final loss to his old City Rovers team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/City Defeat Devonport\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII\n| date = 1925-08-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250817.2.136\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926, 27, 28, and again in 1934 Haddon played in several veteran player exhibition matches. On October 30, 1926 Haddon made an appearance in an end of season game played between well known league veterans at Carlaw Park. Haddon was representing early New Zealand rugby league legends [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = End of Season Games/Veteran Players in Action\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19473\n| date = 1926-11-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19261101.2.138\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The match finished 10-10 and featured the likes of [[Eric Bennett (New Zealand)|Eric Bennett]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], and [[Thomas McClymont]]. In September, 1927 he was chosen in a Devonport United veteran team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby League/Devonport United\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 207\n| date = 1927-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19270902.2.138.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. Then again in October he played for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against \u201cShaver\u201d Hargreaves team. The match featured [[Ernie Asher]], [[Jim Rukutai]], [[Thomas McClymont]], [[Dougie McGregor]], [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|Billy Wynyard]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], and [[Bert Laing]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Relief of Unemployed\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 248\n| date = 1927-10-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19271020.2.150\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He played in another match in 1928 between City and Ponsonby and then again in 1934 once again for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, 24 September\n| date = 1928-09-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280924.2.148.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Charity Day\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXV, Issue 244\n| date = 1934-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19341015.2.153\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n===Mt Albert Selector===\nIn 1935 and 36 Tom Haddon was elected as a selector for the [[Mt Albert Lions|Mt Albert]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Mt Albert United Club\n| page = 16\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 53\n| date = 1936-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360303.2.193\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/The Coming Season\n| page = 14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 87\n| date = 1936-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360413.2.149\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haddon, Tom}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = Tom Haddon\n|fullname       = Thomas Haddon\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        =  \n|position       = {{rlp|LK}}\n|birth_date    = \n|birth_place = New Zealand\n|height         =  \n|weight         =  \n|club1          = [[City Rovers]]\n|year1start     = 1918\n|year1end       = 19\n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 3\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 9\n|club2               = [[North Shore Albions]]\n|year2start          = 1925\n|year2end            = \n|appearances2        = 9 \n|tries2              = 4\n|goals2              = 0\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 12\n|teamA          = Auckland\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 2\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          =1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 2\n|triesB              = 0\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             = 0\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\nTom Haddon was a New Zealand rugby league player. He was Kiwi number 136 after playing two tests for New Zealand against Australia in 1919.\n\n==Early Life==\nIt is unclear where Thomas Haddon was born or raised. The first clear indication of him being in Auckland is with his debut for [[City Rovers]] in the opening game of the [[1918 Auckland Rugby League season]]. There are no records of him being born or marrying in [[New Zealand]]. At the start of 1920 he was thought to have moved to [[Australia]] to play rugby league but there are no records of him playing there after being given permission by the New Zealand Rugby League Council.\n\n==Playing career==\n===City Rovers, Auckland, and New Zealand===\nTom Haddon first appeared for [[City Rovers]] in 1918 in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition, playing for them against [[Grafton Athletic]] in a preliminary round to open the season <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Northern Union/Teams for Saturday/North Shore\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume XLIX, Issue 99\n| date = 1918-04-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19180426.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He scored a try in a Round 3 match against Grafton Athletic at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] where he \u201creceived a cross-kick and scored underneath the posts\u201d with City going on to win 11-10 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championship Matches/Newton V Ponsonby/Grafton V City\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16860\n| date = 1918-05-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180527.2.62.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. He scored against the same opponents in the second round in front of 5,000 spectators again at Victoria Park <ref>{{cite news\n| title =City Defeats Grafton\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16896\n| date = 1918-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180708.2.50\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nHe was selected for the [[Auckland Rugby League team|Auckland]] team in 1918 and played in the first proper inter provincial match that Auckland had played since [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|1915]] (when they played Thames twice, and Lower Waikato once). During the war the [[Auckland rugby League]] had decided to largely cease its representative program. Haddon\u2019s debut was against Canterbury and it resulted in a comfortable 45-9 victory to Auckland with Haddon scoring twice. The match was played in front of 10,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LV| issue=16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1919 Haddon was again playing for City and in a round two match against [[North Shore Albions]] on the Devonport Domain in front of 500 spectators <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Championships Continue/City V North Shore\n| page =5\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17158\n| date = 1919-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190512.2.21.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>. On August 9, Haddon played for Auckland in a match against Hawkes Bay at Eden Park before a crowd of 9,000. Haddon scored 3 tries in a 38 to 13 victory <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVI| issue=17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>. As this was to be his last game for Auckland it meant that he had scored 3 tries for his City team in 2 full seasons but managed to cross the line 5 times for Auckland in just 2 appearance.\n\nHaddon had been picked to tour Australia with the New Zealand team in June and July of 1919 but due to circumstances was unable to make the trip <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football/Northern Union\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 65\n| date = 1920-03-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200316.2.67.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He was however selected for the 3rd and 4th tests against the touring Australian team in August/September <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. On September 6, Tom Haddon became Kiwi number 136 when he played lock in front of 24,300 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]]. New Zealand were defeated 34 to 23 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Inter-Colonial League/The Kiwi and the Kangaroo\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 213\n| date = 1909-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190908.2.129\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. In the third test also played on the Domain New Zealand was heavily beaten by 32 points to 2 with Haddon moving into the prop position <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The Last Test/Australia\u2019s Decisive Win\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume 219, Issue L\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190915.2.98\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nIn April, 1920 [[Auckland Rugby League]] gave its permission for Haddon to \u201cplay in any district outside Auckland\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The Auckland League\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17447\n| date = 1920-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200417.2.80.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then on May 10 the New Zealand Rugby League Council granted him an open transfer to play in Australia as reported in the New Zealand Herald <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The New Zealand Council\n| page = 6\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17467\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200511.2.96.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The [[Auckland Star]] suggesting that he \u201cwill probably play in Australia\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Affairs in Wellington/N.Z. Council Meets\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 112\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200511.2.96\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. It is however unclear as to where he went and if he played rugby league over the following years.\n\n===North Shore Albions===\nIn 1925 Haddon resumed playing rugby league in Auckland, this time however he was to represent the [[North Shore Albions]] who at this time were in fact named [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] after amalgamating with the Sunnyside League Football Club at the start of the 1920 season <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Two Clubs Amalgamate\n| page =6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVII| issue=17436\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200405.2.100\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. The first mention of him in a Devonport uniform is in a match against his old City team at [[Carlaw Park]] where he scored a try <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Another Great Game/City Beat Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 133,\n| date = 1925-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250608.2.147\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The day was significant for other reasons as the teams stood in silence before the kick off out of respect for [[Bill Stormont]] (Kiwi #140) who had died two days earlier. In a July match Haddon scored a try in front of 9,000 spectators at Carlaw Park against [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. Devonport won but not before Haddon was sent off along with Marist\u2019s New Zealand international [[Andrew O\u2019Brien (rugby league)|Jim O\u2019Brien]] after a \u201crough-up\u201d between the two. Devonport won the match 19-11 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Devonport\u2019s Day Out/Marists v Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 145\n| date = 1925-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250622.2.108\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nAfter a July match between Ponsonby and Devonport it was said of Haddon \u201cit is surprising how youth sticks to some footballers. On Saturday the veteran \u2026 was easily Devonport\u2019s best forward. He showed a lot of pace and some of the form displayed several years ago when playing for [[City Rovers|City]]\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football Notes and Comments/The North Shore Players\n| page =6 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19069\n| date = 1925-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250714.2.9.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then against Athletic \u201cHaddon, following up fast secured, and beating several Athletic players, scored behind the posts with three men hanging on to him\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Club Competitions/Athletic v Devonport\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 169\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250720.2.137\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. He scored a second try later in the match after a \u201cpassing rush\u201d in which all the Devonport players took part. Haddon\u2019s final ever senior league match was in a Roope Rooster semi final loss to his old City Rovers team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/City Defeat Devonport\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII\n| date = 1925-08-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250817.2.136\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926, 27, 28, and again in 1934 Haddon played in several veteran player exhibition matches. On October 30, 1926 Haddon made an appearance in an end of season game played between well known league veterans at Carlaw Park. Haddon was representing early New Zealand rugby league legends [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = End of Season Games/Veteran Players in Action\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19473\n| date = 1926-11-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19261101.2.138\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The match finished 10-10 and featured the likes of [[Eric Bennett (New Zealand)|Eric Bennett]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], and [[Thomas McClymont]]. In September, 1927 he was chosen in a Devonport United veteran team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby League/Devonport United\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 207\n| date = 1927-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19270902.2.138.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. Then again in October he played for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against \u201cShaver\u201d Hargreaves team. The match featured [[Ernie Asher]], [[Jim Rukutai]], [[Thomas McClymont]], [[Dougie McGregor]], [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|Billy Wynyard]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], and [[Bert Laing]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Relief of Unemployed\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 248\n| date = 1927-10-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19271020.2.150\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He played in another match in 1928 between City and Ponsonby and then again in 1934 once again for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, 24 September\n| date = 1928-09-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280924.2.148.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Charity Day\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXV, Issue 244\n| date = 1934-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19341015.2.153\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n===Mt Albert Selector===\nIn 1935 and 36 Tom Haddon was elected as a selector for the [[Mt Albert Lions|Mt Albert]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Mt Albert United Club\n| page = 16\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 53\n| date = 1936-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360303.2.193\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/The Coming Season\n| page = 14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 87\n| date = 1936-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360413.2.149\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haddon, Tom}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCity Rovers, Auckland, and New Zealand", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Haddon"}
{"title_page": "Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist \n| name             = Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en\n| background       = temporary\n| image            = Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Jazz p\u00e5 J\u00f8lst 2018 (203506).jpg\n| caption          = Tr\u00f8en at Jazz p\u00e5 J\u00f8lst 2018.\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1992|03|15}}\n| birth_place      = [[Voss]], [[Hordaland]], Norway\n| genre            = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| instrument       = Saxophone\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Quartet <br/>[[Bergen Big Band]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en''' (born 15 March 1992 in [[Voss, Norway]]) is a Norwegian jazz saxophonist, and composer.\n\n== Biography ==\nTr\u00f8en picked up the saxophone at 16 in 2008, and studied jazz at Voss Jazzskule. By the age of 20, she had already played with musicians like [[Terri Lyne Carrington]], [[Tineke Postma]], [[Andy Sheppard]], [[Tord Gustavsen]], and not the least [[Joshua Redman]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://jazzinorge.no/arrangement/elisabeth-lid-troen-kvartett-3 | title=Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Kvartett | language=no | website=JazzINorge.no | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref> In 2013, she played with her own Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Quartet, at [[Vossajazz]], including with pianist [[Erlend Slettevoll]], bassist [[Steinar Raknes]], and drummer [[Erik Nylander]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://vossajazz.no/arrangement/elisabeth-lid-troen-kvartett | title=Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en kvartett | language=no | publisher=[[Vossajazz]] | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref> At the 2014 [[Vossajazz]] she played with [[Signe F\u00f8rre|Signe F\u00f8rre Band]]. The lineup included pianist [[Eivind Austad]], and drummer [[H\u00e5kon Mj\u00e5set Johansen]]. In 2016 Tr\u00f8en continued the collaboration with Tord Gustavsen.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://jazzinorge.no/arrangement/elisabeth-lid-troen-kvartett-3 | title=Lid Tr\u00f8en og Gustavsen i Dale kyrkje | first=Nils | last=Kvamsdal | newspaper=[[Hordaland (newspaper)|Hordaland]] | date=2016-06-13 | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref> At the 2018 Vossajazz Tr\u00f8en appeared with the [[Bergen Big Band]] featuring keyboardist and orchestra leader [[Django Bates]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://vossajazz.no/arrangement/bergen-big-band | title=Django Bates & Bergen Big Band | language=no | website=[[Vossajazz]] | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n* 2011: Awarded the Dr\u00f8mmestipendet (the dream scholarship) by the Norwegian Cultural Education Council<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.drommestipendet.no/nyheter/drommestipendet-2011-gar-til | title=Dr\u00f8mmestipendet 2011 g\u00e5r til\u2026 | language=no | publisher=Drommestipendet.no | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n; With [[Dag Arnesen]] and [[Bergen Big Band]]\n* [[2017 in jazz|2017]]: ''Norwegian Song IV'' ([[Odin Records|Odin]])<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/Bergen-Big-Band-Dag-Arnesen-Norwegian-Song-IV/release/10366931 | title=Bergen Big Band & Dag Arnesen \u2013 Norwegian Song IV | publisher=[[Discogs.com]] | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{portal|Norway|Jazz}}\n{{commonscat}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Troen, Elisabeth Lid}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Female jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Vaksdal]]\n[[Category:Female jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women musicians]]\n[[Category:Bergen Big Band members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist \n| name             = Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en\n| background       = temporary\n| image            = Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Jazz p\u00e5 J\u00f8lst 2018 (203506).jpg\n| caption          = Tr\u00f8en at Jazz p\u00e5 J\u00f8lst 2018.\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1992|03|15}}\n| birth_place      = [[Voss]], [[Hordaland]], Norway\n| genre            = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| instrument       = Saxophone\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Quartet <br/>[[Bergen Big Band]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en''' (born 15 March 1992 in [[Voss, Norway]]) is a Norwegian jazz saxophonist, and composer.\n\n== Biography ==\nTr\u00f8en picked up the saxophone at 16 in 2008, and studied jazz at Voss Jazzskule. When she was 20 se had already played with musicians like [[Terri Lyne Carrington]], [[Tineke Postma]], [[Andy Sheppard]], [[Tord Gustavsen]], and not the least [[Joshua Redman]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://jazzinorge.no/arrangement/elisabeth-lid-troen-kvartett-3 | title=Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Kvartett | language=no | website=JazzINorge.no | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref> In 2013 she played with her own Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en Quartet, at [[Vossajazz]], including with pianist [[Erlend Slettevoll]], bassist [[Steinar Raknes]], and drummer [[Erik Nylander]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://vossajazz.no/arrangement/elisabeth-lid-troen-kvartett | title=Elisabeth Lid Tr\u00f8en kvartett | language=no | publisher=[[Vossajazz]] | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref> At the 2014 [[Vossajazz]] she played with [[Signe F\u00f8rre|Signe F\u00f8rre Band]]. The lineup included pianist [[Eivind Austad]], and drummer [[H\u00e5kon Mj\u00e5set Johansen]]. In 2016 Tr\u00f8en continued the collaboration with Tord Gustavsen.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://jazzinorge.no/arrangement/elisabeth-lid-troen-kvartett-3 | title=Lid Tr\u00f8en og Gustavsen i Dale kyrkje | first=Nils | last=Kvamsdal | newspaper=[[Hordaland (newspaper)|Hordaland]] | date=2016-06-13 | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref> At the 2018 Vossajazz Tr\u00f8en appeared with the [[Bergen Big Band]] featuring keyboardist and orchestra leader [[Django Bates]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://vossajazz.no/arrangement/bergen-big-band | title=Django Bates & Bergen Big Band | language=no | website=[[Vossajazz]] | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n* 2011: Awarded the Dr\u00f8mmestipendet (the dream scolorship) by the Norwegian Cultural Education Council<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.drommestipendet.no/nyheter/drommestipendet-2011-gar-til | title=Dr\u00f8mmestipendet 2011 g\u00e5r til\u2026 | language=no | publisher=Drommestipendet.no | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n; With [[Dag Arnesen]] and [[Bergen Big Band]]\n* [[2017 in jazz|2017]]: ''Norwegian Song IV'' ([[Odin Records|Odin]])<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/Bergen-Big-Band-Dag-Arnesen-Norwegian-Song-IV/release/10366931 | title=Bergen Big Band & Dag Arnesen \u2013 Norwegian Song IV | publisher=[[Discogs.com]] | accessdate=2018-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{portal|Norway|Jazz}}\n{{commonscat}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Troen, Elisabeth Lid}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Female jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Vaksdal]]\n[[Category:Female jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women musicians]]\n[[Category:Bergen Big Band members]]\n", "name_user": "CamWass", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar/spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elisabeth_Lid_Tr%C3%B8en"}
{"title_page": "Salem, Tamil Nadu", "text_new": "{{About|a city in India|other uses|Salem (disambiguation){{!}}Salem}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Salem\n| native_name             = \u0b9a\u0bc7\u0bb2\u0bae\u0bcd\n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = Metropolis \n| image_skyline           = SalemCITYMONTAGE.jpg\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = Clockwise from top right: Hasthampatty roundabout, [[Kiliyur Falls]], Trumpet Exchange at NH544, Salem Steel Plant, Salem district collectorate, [[Modern Theatres]], [[Mookaneri Lake]] and Government Multispeciality Hospital\n| nickname                = [[Steel City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mygov.in/group-issue/my-salem-my-pride/|title=My Salem - My Pride|date=30 October 2015|publisher=[[Government of India]]|access-date=1 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201193418/https://www.mygov.in/group-issue/my-salem-my-pride/|archive-date=1 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> <br /> Mango City\n| map_alt                 = Location of Salem\n| map_caption             =\n| pushpin_map             = India Tamil Nadu\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         =\n| pushpin_map_caption     =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|11.65|N|78.16|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = India\n| subdivision_type1       = State\n| subdivision_type2       = District\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Salem district]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        =\n| founder                 =\n| named_for               =\n| government_type         = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013Council]]\n| governing_body          = [[Salem City Municipal Corporation]]\n| leader_title            = Mayor\n| leader_name             = vacant\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          = 124\n| area_rank               = 5\n| elevation_footnotes     =\n| elevation_m             = 289\n| population_total        = 829,267\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name=2011census/>\n| population_density_km2  = 9079\n| population_metro        = 917,414\n| population_metro_footnotes = <ref name=\"UA_2011\">{{cite web|title=Primary Census Abstract - Urban Agglomeration|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/DigitalLibrary/MFTableSeries.aspx|format=XLS|publisher=[[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India]]|access-date=13 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315050316/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/DigitalLibrary/MFTableSeries.aspx|archive-date=15 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| population_rank         = 5\n| population_note         =\n| demographics_type1      = \nLanguages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = Tamil\n| demographics1_title2    = Spoken\n| demographics1_info2     = Tamil\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 636xxx\n| area_code               = [[Telephone numbers in India|+91-427]]\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| registration_plate     =  TN-27, TN-30, TN-54, TN-90\n| website                 = {{URL|www.salemcorporation.gov.in}}\n| footnotes               =\n| other_name              =\n}}\n'''Salem''' ({{audio|Salem.ogg|pronunciation}}) is a city in [[Salem district]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is located about {{convert|160|km|mi|-1}} northeast of [[Coimbatore]], {{convert|186|km|mi|0}} southeast of Karnataka state capital [[Bangalore]] and about {{convert|340|km|mi|-1}} southwest of the state capital, [[Chennai]]. Salem is the [[List of cities in Tamil Nadu by population|Fifth]]\nlargest city as well as the fifth largest urban agglomeration in the state by population and covers {{convert|124|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and rowdy city in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salemcorporation.gov.in/about-corporation.php|title=About Corporation|publisher=salemcorporation.gov.in|access-date=27 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718231923/http://www.salemcorporation.gov.in/about-corporation.php|archive-date=18 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe town and the surrounding hilly regions were part of the [[Chera dynasty]] and was part of the trade route with the [[Roman empire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsFarEast/IndiaCheras.htm|title=Far East Kingdoms of South Asia: Cheras|work=The History Files|access-date=25 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217112250/http://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsFarEast/IndiaCheras.htm|archive-date=17 February 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was later governed by [[Poligars]], who built temples and forts in and around the city.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Commerce between the Roman Empire and India|author=E. H. Warmington|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2014|isbn=978-1107-432-14-7|page=144}}</ref> It was part of the [[Vijayanagara empire]] before being captured by [[Hyder Ali]] during the early 18th century, after the [[Mangammal#War with Mysore|Mysore-Madurai war]]. It was ceded to the British in 1768 and the area became part of the struggle between [[Kongu Nadu]] led by [[Dheeran Chinnamalai]] and the British.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-in-school/winding-the-clock-back-anticolonial-wise/article6835999.ece|title= Winding the clock back, anti-colonial wise|author=Asha Sridhar|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=30 January 2015|access-date=25 February 2017}}</ref> Salem became part of [[Salem district]] since independence in 1947.\n\n=={{anchor|Geography and Climate}}Geography and climate==\n\nSalem is located at {{Coord|11.67|N|78.14|E|}},<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/25/Salem.html |title=Falling Rain Genomic s, Inc&nbsp;\u2013 Salem |publisher=Fallingrain.com |access-date=10 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013121956/http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/25/Salem.html |archive-date=13 October 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> at an average elevation of 278&nbsp;m (912&nbsp;ft). The city is surrounded by hills: Nagaramalai on the north, Jarugumalai on the south, [[Kanjamalai]] on the west, [[Godumalai]] on the east and the [[Shevaroy Hills]] on the northeast. Kariyaperumal Hill is in southwestern Salem.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/people-throng-tourist-spots-on-kaanum-pongal/article6798283.ece|title=People throng tourist spots on 'Kaanum Pongal'|author=Syed Muthahar Saqaf|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=18 January 2015|access-date=5 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205131013/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/people-throng-tourist-spots-on-kaanum-pongal/article6798283.ece|archive-date=5 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Thirumanimutharu River]] flows through the city, dividing it in two.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/river-thirumanimuthar-cries-for-attention/article7804532.ece|title=River Thirumanimuthar cries for attention|author=SS.P. Saravanan|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=26 October 2015|access-date=5 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130548/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/river-thirumanimuthar-cries-for-attention/article7804532.ece|archive-date=5 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The fort area is the oldest part of Salem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonatech.ac.in/about-sona/salem-district.html|title=ABOUT SALEM CITY|publisher=sonatech.in|accessdate=February 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424005956/http://www.sonatech.ac.in/about-sona/salem-district.html|archive-date=24 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSalem lies in the foothills of Shevaroy hills which houses the famous hill Station Yercaud.\n\nSalem has a [[tropical savanna climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Aw''). January and February are generally pleasant; the hot summer begins in March, with the year's highest temperatures during April. Pre-monsoon thunderstorms occur during April and May. The Southwest monsoon season lasts from June to September. The [[Monsoon#Northeast monsoon|northeast monsoon]] occurs from October to December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgwb.gov.in/District_Profile/TamilNadu/Salem.pdf|title=DISTRICT GROUNDWATER BROCHURE SALEM DISTRICT, TAMIL NADU|publisher=Central Ground Water Board|accessdate=February 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403092016/http://cgwb.gov.in/District_Profile/TamilNadu/Salem.pdf|archive-date=3 April 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnenvis.nic.in/WriteReadData/UserFiles/file/9_SALEM_RAINFALL.pdf|title=Ground Water Augmentation Of Kannankuruchi Lake, Salem, TamilNadu Using GIS|publisher=International Journal of Emerging Trends & Technology in Computer Science (IJETTCS)|accessdate=February 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184519/http://www.tnenvis.nic.in/WriteReadData/UserFiles/file/9_SALEM_RAINFALL.pdf|archive-date=5 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Salem, Tamil Nadu (1981\u20132010, extremes 1901\u20132012)\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line = Yes\n| width = auto\n| Jan record high C = 37.2\n| Feb record high C = 39.4\n| Mar record high C = 41.7\n| Apr record high C = 42.8\n| May record high C = 42.8\n| Jun record high C = 42.8\n| Jul record high C = 40.6\n| Aug record high C = 39.9\n| Sep record high C = 38.9\n| Oct record high C = 37.9\n| Nov record